QUESTION:
Input: nums = [1,2,3]
Output: [[],[1],[2],[1,2],[3],[1,3],[2,3],[1,2,3]]
SOLUTION:
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
TIME  COMPLEXITY:O(n*2^n)
SPACE COMPLEXITY:O(n*2^n)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
This is a proper backtracking problem.
[1 2 3]
[] [1] [1 2] [1 2 3] [2] [2 3] [3]

Start with empty:
[]
Pick 1:
[1]
[1,2]
[1,2,3]
→ No more elements → backtrack
Backtrack:
[1,2,3] → [1,2]
From [1,2]:
→ No more choices → backtrack
Backtrack:
[1,2] → [1]
From [1]:
→ Pick 3 → [1,3]
→ No more elements → backtrack
Backtrack:
[1,3] → [1] → []
Pick 2:
[2]
[2,3]
→ No more elements → backtrack
Backtrack:
[2,3] → [2] → []
Pick 3:
[3]
→ No more elements → backtrack
Backtrack:
[3] → []
Final Result:
[[], [1], [1,2], [1,2,3], [1,3], [2], [2,3], [3]]

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
CODE:
class Solution {
    List<List<Integer>>result=new ArrayList<>();
    public List<List<Integer>> subsets(int[] nums) {
        backtrack(nums,new ArrayList<>(),0);
        return result;
    }
    public void backtrack(int[] nums,ArrayList<Integer>temp,int index){
        if(index>nums.length)return;
        result.add(new ArrayList<>(temp));
        for(int i=index;i<nums.length;i++){
            temp.add(nums[i]);
            backtrack(nums,temp,i+1);
            temp.remove(temp.size()-1);
        }
    }
}
